comments.body:
Thank you for the clarifications. In any case, I will make sure to add `sudo` when posting examples, so that they become more clear. 

I also performed some checks and:
* running `podman inspect` on the running containers seems to confirm the use of the bridged network;
* I also see no difference in the output of `podman inspect` if I force the use of the bridge by adding `--network=bridge` on command line;
* adding `--network=bridge` to the outer container in my [last example](https://github.com/containers/libpod/issues/5188#issuecomment-586184501) makes no difference (network connectivity is lost when the inner container is started);
* adding `--network=bridge` to the inner container, too, makes no difference either: also, no error related to permissions is raised.

Also, you might have noticed that, in an effort of reducing permissions as much as possible, I removed `--privileged` in my last example and am using `--cap-add CAP_NET_ADMIN --volume /dev/net/tun` instead (I get permission errors without those).
It seems to me that those capabilities somehow allow podman to interfere with the host network setup... might this be a plausible theory?

@giuseppe Thank you very much for your input. This one looks like a viable solution.

I run exactly your code, and it seems to work: the last `apt-get -y update` properly connects to the internet. However, If we remove the `sed` command, we have the same behaviour described in the OP.

I will now try to implement this solution in my application, and report back if further roadblocks arise. Meanwhile, may I ask how we should regard this issue? Is it due to "user incompetence" or is it something that podman should handle automatically (and we can hope to see a PR in the future)?
